posts.name: Jackson Yoes
posts.cooked:
your tuner values look ok, you probably want to tune the PID better for your steer if you are getting a rattling sound from the gears.

i see you have 60 amps for a current limit on the stators. this should be fine, but that significant of a voltage drop is weird. Are you using new batteries, and have you checked that the connections are tight and correct?

im not much of a code person so im not sure if you are setting a drive motor current limit. I see that you have wheel slip current, but im not sure if that actually applies. Hopefully someone else can chime in on that.

posts.name: Jackson Yoes
posts.cooked:
This is a very good post on deciding how to set current limits. Generally from what ive seen people set their supply current limit to 60-80 amps. You need to test this though, and the post explains very well how you might do that.

I think the code for setting current limits is something like

config.CurrentLimits.SupplyCurrentLimitEnable = true; config.CurrentLimits.SupplyCurrentLimit = 80; (put how many amps you decide on here)

CTRE also provides examples

make sure your batteries are making GOOD connection. If its loose or not all the way in a port you will get performance hits.

posts.name: s-neff
posts.cooked:
“Wiring is a hot mess but I don’t think there’s anything severly wrong” is a red flag.

Browning out on a electrical quality issue would result in steering motions failing to complete - voltage sag down to brownout, motor cuts, voltage recovers, action completes.

Check the weird stuff - incomplete crimped lug, incomplete ferrule crimp, stripback length into to the PDH , crimp flash on the SB50 contacts preventing the contacts from seating properly, bad spring in the old SB50 not holding the contact, some insulation trapped in the wrong place somewhere…

posts.name: Allen Nuttle
posts.cooked: Try up in the air – if your steer isn’t right, the drive motors can wind up fighting each other, which can cause current draw to be really high.  Get the steering right before you try to drive.

posts.name: Myer

posts.name: Allen Nuttle
posts.cooked:
OK, that’s helpful.  It’s odd that steering is causing the drops.  You should look at the current data for those motors, to see if it is only one of the four, or if they are all similar.  If you do have one with a noticeably higher current draw, check that that module isn’t any harder to turn by hand (with the robot off) and check the mechanical assembly of that module carefully.

You could also disconnect all but one steering motor (remove the breaker) at a time to check to see if you can find one that’s causing the trouble.  Report the current numbers you are seeing for the different modules steering motors and we should be able to help pin things down.
When powered off… do the swerve modules turn freely?

posts.name: Allen Nuttle

Sorry for the delay – busy weekend.

Running steering motors while up on blocks should certainly not cause such issues.  I’ll look at the logs soon, but if the problem is there for each of the four steering motors, I’d look carefully at the wiring – especially the main power loop, and make sure you have a good battery. posts.name: Benjamin Hall
posts.cooked:
To add on to this, we have documentation on current limits and when you need them: Improving Performance with Current Limits .

In your case, those logs show about 75 A of current draw from the Kraken X60 motors, but the supply voltage dropping from 11.9 V to 6.2 V. As mentioned in the Preventing Brownouts section, it’s likely that there’s an electrical issue at play here that should be investigated, as I would expect that kind of voltage drop with 280 A of current draw, not 75 A. I would check all four of the bullet points mentioned in our documentation before considering anything software-side like current limits.

posts.name: Allen Nuttle
posts.cooked:
image 1052×472 35.9 KB

image 1052×472 35.9 KB

image 1052×472 35.9 KB

This is pointing to wiring I think – it’s hard to be sure from afar, so don’t lock in on only wiring, but I’d check it carefully, including the gauge wire you are using and all connections.  Also try different batteries.

There are two different patterns in the data I’ve graphed here.  I picked data from all the Talon-FX motor controllers, and zoomed in on the region where things are enabled.  I graphed supply voltage from one motor (voltage values on right labels), plus supply current from all of these (amperage values on left labels).  I turned off the current data for the motors that weren’t drawing much at all (this turned out to be all of the even-numbered motors, so only four odd-numbered ones are shown – I assume these are the four steering motors).

In general, notice that the voltage drops when the total current rises.  This is Ohm’s law and you are showing a whole lot of drop for relatively low current draw, which points to wiring/battery.  This is easiest to see in the portion of the graph near the center, plus a very similar repeat that’s just to the right (so just a little later in time).  Just going by eye, less than 30 Amps total current draw is bringing you down to the brownout protection voltage.

The two parts of the graph to the left of center are even worse, but it’s a bit hard to read.  It does look as though there were two different things happening in this test.  But the big picture is pointing to way too much resistance.  Post wiring pics when you can.

posts.name: Alex Tsekhansky
Jackson Yoes
posts.cooked:
Ok, Hi again. I was just thinking about your post as we finished our season. We had some pretty bad brownout issues with new batteries this year, even when fully charged. We kept turning down our drive current limits, but we were still getting voltage sag pretty badly. We would be sitting still and be rocking 10 volts.

Turns out the screw terminals in 1-2 of our krakens were broken off and were not making proper connections. We used the torque wrenches on all of the terminals, so I don’t really know how this happened, but you would undo the cover, and the power wire(s) would just come right out, lug and all.

After we discovered this and replaced the affected motors, our brownout issues suddenly disappeared.

I would check each and every single terminal on the Krakens you are running on your robot. Sorry, I didn’t catch this sooner! I hope your season went well!
